{"author":{"id":"783b610f274a0d93f6239db0fc75d0982606c877a4661d3aea84b42bc3a85cea"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1520051228,"nonce":"uDAkqq4npuyVDEN9mcJcKfO2WQI=","metadata":{"github-id":"MDU6SXNzdWUzMDE5Njc1MTI=","github-url":"https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/1754","origin":"github"},"title":"FeatureCounts 1.6.0.2 has the first \"built-in\" Gene annotation file auto-selected. Would avoid usage errors to require active selection.","message":"**Tool**: featureCounts Measure gene expression in RNA-Seq experiments from SAM or BAM files. (Galaxy Version 1.6.0.2)\n\nUsers do not always notice when an option is pre-filled on a tool form.\n\nI can select an input with the database metadata set as \"mm10\" but still have a form filled out with \"hg38\", the first index available, selected.\n\nEnhancement ideas to avoid usage problems:\n\n - **Force users to actively choose a built-in annotation file**. Meaning, the default on the tool form would be blank or \"unspecified (?)\". \n - **If nothing is chosen, do NOT submit the job**, but give a warning on the tool form that a selection must be made (built-in or from the history).\n - We could **use the input database metadata to auto-select annotation, if the input database matches one of the built-in indexes**. Nice to have, but is a niche use-case if there are only 4 indexed annotations available. \n - AND, **IF there is a mismatch between the input datatype assignment and the built-in annotation selected (not for history annotation), also do not submit the job**, instead, warn the user at submission that they need to correct the mismatch. Mapping tools always tag the BAM/SAM output with the genome/database used for mapping -- unless a custom genome is used, which would not use one of the built-in annotations anyway.\n\nMany existing tools do one of the above. It avoids very common usage errors -often users do not even notice the problem until some downstream tool errors or produces odd results. This is frustrating after doing the heavy lifting of getting through many mapping jobs + intermediate tools that might not fail but produce odd but unnoticed results. All jobs have to be rerun from the start when the wrong built-in index is used.\n\nWe are considering doing the same for more tools (mapping tools as a priority https://github.com/galaxyproject/galaxy/issues/4499) that have still built-in indexes auto-selected. **These are passively and randomly \"selected\"** - what is used is just the first in the index list on that server. Instead, tools should require actively-selected built-in indexes/genomes at runtime or data mismatch problems result.\n\nDiscussion welcome - just trying to make things easier for our end-users. Alternative ideas/solutions are great.","files":null}]}